<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-07T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-07T09:00:00-05:00" n="155" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d155">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">340.1115A/833: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-07T15:00:00+01:00">June
                                        7, 1940—3 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received June 7—1:16 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>481. My 465, June 5, 3 p.m., and 459, June 4, 11 a.m.<note n="90" xml:id="d155fn90">Neither printed.</note> In reply to my inquiry
                                this morning Ciano informed me definitely that the <hi rend="italic">Rex</hi> would not sail and added that I had been right in
                                recommending that the <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi> should not
                                plan to enter the Mediterranean.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>